== __**Using ROS on a RasperryPi for Image Transport with Simulink as development tool**__ ==&#xd;
&#xd;
----&#xd;
&#xd;
Notes:&#xd;
&#xd;
* //To be abled to use this Tutorial you need to have the “MATLAB-” and “SIMULINK Support Package for Raspberry Pi” installed. You also need the official “Robotics System Toolbox” from MATLAB/SIMULINK.//&#xd;
* //Use a Raspberrypi 3 B v1.2 or an earlier Version to set up the Raspberry with the “MATLAB/SIMULINK Support Package for Raspberry Pi”, otherwise you will receive a network Error due to incompatibility.&#xd;
(State of 09/2018)&#xd;
 //&#xd;
* //It’s helpful to execute the following Tutorials beforehand:&#xd;
(link)&#xd;
(link)//&#xd;
&#xd;
----&#xd;
&#xd;
== **Introduction** ==&#xd;
&#xd;
We want to stream an RGB-image from a ROS-node on a RaspberryPi to another ROS-node on a virtual machine.&#xd;
To work with MATLAB/SIMULINK on a RaspberryPi we need to set up the RaspberryPi with a modified Linux distribution which is provided by the Simulink Support Package for Raspberri Pi.&#xd;
This Tutorial assumes you understand the Basics of ROS and ROS in MATLAB/SIMULINK. We base our model on the following MATLAB/SIMULINK example:&#xd;
(Link)&#xd;
&#xd;
----&#xd;
&#xd;
=== **Setup your Raspberry:** ===&#xd;
&#xd;
----&#xd;
&#xd;
**Install Linux on your Raspberry**&#xd;
&#xd;
* Install the "Simulink Support Package for Raspberry Pi"&#xd;
&#xd;
* Open Matlab and click on the “Add-Ons”-button>>”Manage Add-Ons”.&#xd;
&#xd;
* Search for “Simulink Support Package for Raspberry Pi”-tab in the list.&#xd;
&#xd;
* Click on the “Setup”-button on the right-hand side of the tab.(A small gear wheel)&#xd;
&#xd;
* Chose the Version of the Raspberry Pi you use and click “Next”.&#xd;
&#xd;
* Chose “Setup Hardware with MathWorks Raspbian Image” and follow the instructions.&#xd;
&#xd;
* After the Setup when you start the Raspberry Pi for the first time execute the command:&#xd;
&#xd;
>{{html}}&lt;font size="2">sudo raspi-config&lt;/font>{{/html}}&#xd;
&#xd;
* Navigate to change hostname and change your keyboard setting and the default Hostname to a distinct one by executing:&#xd;
&#xd;
>{{html}}&lt;font size="2">sudo grep -lr "{ALTER_NAME}" /etc/*&lt;/font>{{/html}}&#xd;
&#xd;
This is to make sure the old Hostname doesn’t appear in any systemic file.&#xd;
&#xd;
* Restart the RaspberryPi.&#xd;
&#xd;
----&#xd;
&#xd;
**Install ROS on your RaspberryPi**&#xd;
&#xd;
After you've installed the Operation System of your Raspberry follow the instructions of the Install_ROS Tutorial.&#xd;
&#xd;
----&#xd;
&#xd;
**Set up a connection from MATLAB/SIMULINK to your Raspberry Pi:**&#xd;
&#xd;
&#xd;
To set up a connection between your Raspberry Pi and MATLAB you need to know the Hostname or the IP-Address of your Raspberry Pi.&#xd;
&#xd;
When your Raspberry Pi is connected to your machine and running open MATLAB and execute the command:&#xd;
&#xd;
>{{html}}&lt;font size="2">rpi=raspberrypi(‘{RPi_IP}’);&lt;/font>{{/html}}&#xd;
&#xd;
(replace rpi with a variable-identifier of your choice)&#xd;
&#xd;
No you have an object which represents your RaspberryPi holding its IP and other information.&#xd;
If you execute the command:&#xd;
&#xd;
>{{html}}&lt;font size="2">openShell(RaspiObj)&lt;/font>{{/html}}&#xd;
&#xd;
You can execute commands on your Raspberry from your platform using Matlab from this Shell.</content>
</xwikidoc>@


